          {
            "text": "Toss and dress",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Dice {{apple-eating}} of eating apple and toss immediately with the juice of {{lemon}} lemon. Add {{celery}} of sliced celery stalks, {{raisins}} of raisins and {{walnuts}} of walnuts. Mix {{mayonnaise}} of mayonnaise with {{plain-yoghurt}} of yoghurt, {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt and {{black-pepper}} of pepper. Fold the dressing through the salad until everything is coated. Serve on a bed of lettuce leaves if using.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Dress the apple in lemon juice the moment it is cut. Work quickly; once the flesh is exposed to air, browning begins.",
              "cause": "Not tossed in lemon juice immediately after cutting.",
              "symptom": "Apple browning before serving"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The yoghurt thins the dressing and adds a faint acidity that prevents it from feeling cloying.",
              "cause": "Full mayonnaise without the yoghurt to lighten.",
              "symptom": "Dressing too heavy and rich"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add the walnuts no more than 30 minutes before serving.",
              "cause": "Salad made too far ahead with walnuts already in.",
              "symptom": "Walnuts go soft"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The Waldorf salad is one of the few hotel dishes that entered the domestic repertoire unchanged. The combination has lasted 130 years because it works: sweet, crisp, nutty and lightly dressed. It belongs on a buffet table, next to cold chicken or ham, or as a lunch on its own. The yoghurt twist is modern but appropriate.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
